Subject: Build Specification for Spending Graph MCP Tool

Dear Coding Agent,

I want you to design and implement a dedicated MCP graph tool for our finance chatbot application. The application stack is TypeScript + Node.js + Next.js, and the chatbot uses the GPT API for conversation. This graph tool must allow authenticated users to view visual summaries of their saved financial data, including categories such as rent, food, subscriptions, daily spending, transportation, utilities, and other expenses.

The goal of this tool is to provide a reliable and structured way for the chatbot to request chart data, while ensuring that all calculations, aggregations, and formatting are handled by backend logic rather than the language model itself.

Primary Objective

Create a graph-focused MCP tool that reads a user’s saved financial data and returns structured chart-ready data for frontend rendering. The tool should support at minimum:

bar graphs
pie graphs

These graphs should help users understand:

category-based spending
time-based spending trends
relative proportion of expenses
high-level financial patterns

The language model should explain the result in natural language, but it must not perform the graph math itself. All totals, aggregations, percentages, and filters must come from deterministic backend logic.

Core Functional Requirements

The graph MCP tool must support the following use cases:

Show a user’s spending by category for a selected date range
Show monthly spending totals over time
Show yearly spending summaries
Show filtered visualizations based on selected categories
Support both bar and pie chart output modes
Allow the frontend to re-render graphs when category filters or date ranges change

At MVP level, the graph tool must at least support:

yearly spending by category
monthly spending trend
pie chart of expense distribution
category filtering
Authentication and Data Ownership

This tool must be treated as a protected MCP tool.

Requirements:

only authenticated users can access their graph data
the tool must never accept a raw user ID from the model as trusted input
the authenticated application session must determine the active user
all queries must enforce user ownership at the database and service level
users must only be able to access their own spending records

The model must not decide authorization. Authorization must be enforced entirely server-side.

Architecture Requirements

The graph tool should follow this architecture:

Frontend

The frontend should:

provide user controls for graph type, date range, and category filters
render the graph using chart-ready JSON returned by the backend
support switching between bar and pie views
display summaries and loading/error states
GPT Layer

The GPT layer should:

understand the user’s request
choose the graph tool when appropriate
explain the graph output in plain language
MCP Tool Layer

The MCP tool should:

receive validated chart request parameters
fetch the authenticated user’s relevant financial data
aggregate and compute totals
generate structured output for chart rendering
return deterministic and consistent results
Business Logic Layer

The business logic should:

calculate grouped expense totals
compute percentages for pie charts
calculate totals for date ranges
support grouping by category and month
prepare reusable chart datasets
Persistence Layer

The database layer should:

store transactions and categories in normalized form
support efficient date-range and category-based queries
enforce ownership through user-linked records
Tool Design Requirements

Create a dedicated tool, such as:

get_spending_chart_data

This tool should support inputs such as:

chart type
grouping mode
date range
selected year or month
included categories

Possible parameters include:

chartType: bar or pie
groupBy: category or month
startDate
endDate
year
includeCategories

The exact schema should be defined and documented clearly.

The tool output must be structured, predictable, and chart-ready. At minimum it should include:

title
chart type
labels
values
currency
total
selected date range
selected categories
basic highlights such as largest category or highest month

The output must be designed for frontend rendering rather than prose generation.

Data Model Requirements

Ensure the financial storage model supports graph generation cleanly.

At minimum, the data model should account for:

users
transactions
categories
optional budgets for future graph comparisons

Transaction records should support:

user linkage
amount
transaction date
merchant or description
category assignment
transaction type

Category records should support:

category name
stable identifier or slug
optional display metadata for UI use later
Spec and Sprint Requirements

Create a dedicated spec for this graph tool inside:

docs/spec_folder

This spec must include:

feature name
purpose
business value
user stories
functional requirements
non-functional requirements
acceptance criteria
tool input schema requirements
tool output schema requirements
UI behavior expectations
validation rules
security requirements
ownership enforcement requirements
logging and observability
dependencies
testing requirements

Then convert this spec into implementation sprints.

Each sprint must include:

sprint goal
concrete implementation tasks
test tasks
deliverables
risks
done criteria
UI/UX Requirements

The graph experience should be practical and easy to use.

At MVP level, include:

graph type toggle between bar and pie
date range selector
category filter checkboxes
summary label above or near the chart
empty state when no data exists
error state when loading fails

The UI should not depend on the model to format chart data. It should only consume structured data from the graph tool.

Validation Requirements

All tool inputs must be strictly validated.

Validate:

allowed chart types
valid date ranges
valid category filters
supported grouping modes
empty data conditions
malformed requests
unauthorized access attempts

Return safe, consistent errors for invalid requests.

Logging and Observability

The system must log graph tool usage in a useful way.

At minimum log:

authenticated user context
tool name
timestamp
requested chart type
date range
selected categories
success or failure result
validation or authorization failures

Do not expose sensitive internal details in user-facing responses.

Testing Requirements

You must define and implement:

positive tests
negative tests
edge case tests

These must be included across:

unit tests
integration tests
end-to-end tests
Unit tests should cover:
category aggregation logic
monthly grouping logic
percentage calculations for pie charts
empty dataset handling
validation logic
label/value formatting
Integration tests should cover:
authenticated tool execution
database queries for user-owned transactions
graph dataset generation from stored records
filtered queries by category and date range
blocked unauthorized access
invalid parameter handling
End-to-end tests should cover:
logged-in user requests spending graph
chatbot invokes graph tool
graph renders correctly in UI
category filters update graph results
switching bar to pie works correctly
empty-state behavior for users without data
unauthorized users are prevented from access

Be explicit about positive, negative, and edge cases for each of these layers.

Engineering Standards

The implementation must follow:

SOLID principles
appropriate Gang of Four patterns where useful
clean separation of concerns
deterministic calculations
reusable service abstractions
clear interfaces between UI, tool execution, business logic, and persistence

Do not over-engineer the solution, but do not allow graph logic to become mixed directly into the chat layer.

MVP Acceptance Criteria

This feature is considered complete at MVP level when:

an authenticated user can request a spending graph
the backend returns correct chart-ready data
the frontend renders a bar or pie chart correctly
category and date filters work
the model explains the result using tool data
unauthorized access is blocked
test coverage exists across unit, integration, and e2e layers
the feature is documented in docs/spec_folder
Deliverables

I expect the following deliverables:

a dedicated graph MCP tool spec in docs/spec_folder
a sprint breakdown for graph tool implementation
the tool schema definitions
backend aggregation and formatting logic
authenticated graph data access
frontend graph rendering integration
unit, integration, and e2e test coverage
documentation of how the graph feature works and how it is extended later
Execution Guidance

Work systematically. Start by defining the graph feature boundary, then the tool schema, then the data aggregation logic, then the UI contract, then the tests.

Do not implement this as a loose visualization helper. Implement it as a proper product feature with a clear contract between the chat system, the MCP tool, and the frontend.